{"type":"message","id":"2ed8ec57","parentId":"2994ab7f","timestamp":"2026-03-23T06:14:17.784Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The streaming chat endpoint works fine! It returns SSE with text deltas. So the backend is working correctly. The issue must be in the frontend's SSE parsing. Let me look at the frontend JS streaming code again.\n\nLooking at the frontend code:\n```javascript\nconst reader = r.body.getReader();\nconst decoder = new TextDecoder();\nlet novaDiv = addMessage(\"nova\", \"\");\n\nlet buffer = \"\";\n\nwhile (true) {\n  const { value, done } = await reader.read();\n  if (done) break;\n\n  buffer += decoder.decode(value, { stream: true });\n\n  const lines = buffer.split(\"\\n\");\n  buffer = lines.pop() || \"\";\n\n  for (const line of lines) {\n    if (!line.startsWith(\"data:\")) continue;\n    const dataStr = line.slice(5).trim();\n    if (!dataStr) continue;\n\n    try {\n      const event = JSON.parse(dataStr);\n\n      if (event.type === \"text\") {\n        novaDiv.querySelector(\".message-bubble\").textContent += event.content;\n        const messages = document.getElementById(\"chat-messages\");\n        messages.scrollTop = messages.scrollHeight;\n      } else if (event.type === \"done\" || event.type === \"error\") {\n        if (event.type === \"error\") {\n          novaDiv.querySelector(\".message-bubble\").textContent +=\n            \"\\n[Error: \" + event.content + \"]\";\n        }\n        break;\n      }\n    } catch {}\n  }\n}\n```\n\nI see it—after the `done` event breaks from the loop, there's leftover data sitting in the buffer that never gets processed. The loop exits before handling any remaining content that wasn't flushed through a complete SSE line. There's a separate check after the loop that attempts to parse the buffer, but it's looking for a different structure than what's actually there.\n\nLet me trace through the actual SSE format the backend produces. It's sending `data: {\"type\": \"text\", \"content\": \"...\"}\\n\\n` followed by `data: {\"type\": \"done\"}\\n\\n`. The event type check uses `obj.get(\"type\")` which works for both objects and dictionary-style access, so that's not the issue.\n\nBut the backend code shows it's decoding UTF-8 with replacement errors, then manually building SSE lines with `yield f\"data: {json.dumps({'type': 'text', 'content': delta})}\\n\\n\".encode(\"utf-8\")`. The real problem might be in how the buffering works—when `chunk` is read as bytes and decoded, there could be a mismatch between what gets buffered and how the split on `\\n` is actually working. The SSE format the backend generates uses double newlines as delimiters (`data: {...}\\n\\n`), but the frontend's `split(\"\\n\")` only splits on single newlines. This means each line gets processed separately without proper event boundary detection, and events might be getting parsed incorrectly or cut off mid-data.\n\nLet me trace through a concrete example: if the backend sends `data: {\"type\": \"text\", \"content\": \"Hello\"}\\n\\ndata: {\"type\": \"done\"}\\n\\n`, the split on `\"\\n\"` would give individual lines like `\"data: {\\\"type\\\": \\\"text\\\", \\\"content\\\": \\\"Hello\\\"}\"` and `\"data: {\\\"type\\\": \\\"done\\\"}\"`. The issue is that without checking for the double newline boundary, the code might be trying to parse incomplete JSON or missing the actual event completion signals.\n\nBut wait—the curl test actually worked and returned the data correctly, so the backend is functioning. The real problem might be that the UI is making requests to the gateway at `http://127.0.0.1:8765/` but the JavaScript fetch calls are going to `/api/*` which would be relative to where the page loaded from. If the HTML page is being served from somewhere unexpected, those API calls could be hitting the wrong endpoint or not reaching the backend at all.\n\nThe \"Connecting...\" message persists, which suggests either the `/api/status` call is failing silently, or the browser's making a direct gateway request that fails due to CORS or token issues. I should check if the backend is actually running and what the response looks like.","thinkingSignature":"666ea2e6ba1fa5f5a791e841b0c8a2311010bf59f3325e003b504d88bac50edb"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_59f5ib8rc2a1_1","name":"process","arguments":{"action":"log","sessionId":"dawn-cloud","limit":30}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax-portal","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":23478,"output":924,"cacheRead":13506,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":37908,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1774246425024}}
