{"type":"message","id":"7b05883c","parentId":"a4b450fd","timestamp":"2026-03-23T06:15:50.782Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The SSE format looks correct:\n- `data: {\"type\": \"text\", \"content\": \"Hey! ✨\"}\\n\\n`\n- `data: {\"type\": \"done\"}\\n\\n`\n\nEach line is properly terminated with `\\n\\n` (0x0a 0x0a). The format looks right.\n\nNow let me trace through the frontend parsing. The issue must be in the frontend JS. Let me look at the `sendMessage()` function in the HTML:\n\n```javascript\nasync function sendMessage() {\n    if (sending) return;\n    const input = document.getElementById(\"chat-input\");\n    const text = input.value.trim();\n    if (!text) return;\n\n\n```\n\nDisabling the send button, adding the user's message to the chat, showing a typing indicator, then fetching from `/api/chat` with the message text. If the response isn't ok, I remove the typing indicator and display an error with the status and response text.\n\nNow I'm setting up a reader to stream the response body, decoding each chunk and accumulating it in a buffer. I split the buffer by newlines and process each line, extracting JSON data from SSE-formatted responses. When I get a text event, I append the content to Nova's message bubble and scroll to keep it in view.\n\nFor done or error events, I break out of the stream—errors get appended to the message bubble with the error content. Once the stream finishes, I check if there's any remaining data in the buffer and try to parse it as JSON to extract any final text. If anything throws during streaming, I catch it, remove the typing indicator, and show a connection error. Finally, I re-enable the send button and refresh the personality display.\n\nNow I'm realizing the actual problem: the SSE data from the server comes in as `data: {\"type\": \"text\", \"content\": \"Hey! ✨\"}\\n\\n` which decodes to a single line. When I split on `\\n`, the first part gives me the complete SSE message with the JSON object, and the second part is empty. But there's likely an issue with how the double newline is being handled across chunk boundaries. The issue is that `split(\"\\n\")` with a string argument treats `\\n` as a single character delimiter, so each `\\n` creates a new array element. When the buffer contains `data: {...}\\n\\ndata: {...}\\n\\n`, splitting on `\\n` gives me individual lines rather than complete SSE events. The first element is `data: {\"type\": \"text\"...` and the second is an empty string from the double newline, then the next `data: {...}` becomes the third element. This means I'm processing incomplete events instead of waiting for complete ones.\n\nLet me trace through the actual chunk more carefully. If a single TCP packet contains both events with the literal bytes `}\\n\\ndata: {\"type\"...}`, then after the first yield the buffer has that complete chunk. When I split on `\\n`, I get the SSE-formatted text event followed by an empty element from the double newline, which would give me `[\"data: {...}\", \"\", \"data: {...}\"]` instead of processing each event separately.\n\nThe key issue is that with streaming responses, multiple SSE events can arrive in one chunk, and I need to make sure I'm not accidentally concatenating them or missing event boundaries.\n\nWhen the first chunk arrives with both events, `split(\"\\n\")` gives me individual lines, but I'm only processing the first `data:` line and leaving the second one in the buffer for the next iteration. That should actually be fine for correctness, though it might cause a slight timing issue.\n\nThen a second chunk arrives with `{\"type\":...` and the loop continues parsing. The problem is the last element doesn't have a newline after it in the chunk itself, so when I `pop()` it stays in the buffer for the next iteration. This should still work correctly, but I'm wondering if there's a timing issue where the `done` event fires before all chunks are processed, or if the stream is closing prematurely.\n\nLooking at the actual SSE format, each event ends with a newline after its data. So `data: {...}\\n\\n` means the `split(\"\\n\")` will produce elements where the last one before an empty line is the complete event data. The logic should handle this correctly, so maybe the real issue is something else—perhaps the stream is being consumed too quickly or the decoder isn't handling the chunks properly.\n\nWait, I think I found it. The empty catch block `} catch {}` is silently swallowing JSON parsing errors. If the SSE line isn't valid JSON for some reason, the error gets suppressed and the loop continues waiting for more data. That could cause the stream to stall if the parsing keeps failing on each line.\n\nBut actually, looking at the logs again - `sendMessage()` calls `loadStatus()` in the finally block, and that could be throwing an error that's being silently caught somewhere. Or maybe the issue is that SSE data is arriving as multiple chunks, and the text content isn't being properly reconstructed in the message bubble because the chunks aren't being concatenated correctly before parsing.\n\nActually, I think I see it now. The problem might be with how the decoding and buffering works across chunks. When `decoder.decode(value, { stream: true })` is called repeatedly, it returns progressively more decoded text, but the buffer split logic might be losing parts of the SSE format - specifically the `\\n\\n` boundaries that separate events could get mangled if a chunk boundary falls right at that point. I think the issue might actually be a JavaScript error being silently caught, or something more fundamental like a CORS problem. But CORS shouldn't be the culprit since the HTML page is served from the same origin. Let me just have Zach open the browser console to see what's actually happening—that'll give me the real error message instead of guessing. Actually, I should also test what happens when a request gets aborted or takes too long, since that could be triggering an exception that the catch block is swallowing. Let me reconsider the frontend code more carefully and add some defensive handling around the SSE parsing to see if that's where things are breaking down.","thinkingSignature":"f0b4041dc784b9d931734060f9401bbba6584f63607aa00652d0d1f5fb38ad98"},{"type":"text","text":"The streaming works fine via curl. Let me check the actual frontend error — open the browser DevTools (F12) and look at the Console tab. More likely though the issue is the SSE parsing is throwing silently. Let me look:\n"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_r4wfey09tb2s_1","name":"read","arguments":{"path":"C:\\Users\\Zwmar\\Claw\\projects\\nova-ui\\frontend\\index.html","offset":295,"limit":80}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax-portal","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":26121,"output":1383,"cacheRead":13506,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":41010,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1774246500734}}
{"type":"message","id":"e9885146","parentId":"7b05883c","timestamp":"2026-03-23T06:15:50.810Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_function_r4wfey09tb2s_1","toolName":"read","content":[{"type":"text","text":"      cursor: pointer;\r\n      display: flex;\r\n      align-items: center;\r\n      justify-content: center;\r\n      font-size: 16px;\r\n      transition: background 0.15s, transform 0.1s;\r\n      flex-shrink: 0;\r\n    }\r\n\r\n    .chat-send:hover { background: var(--accent-dim); }\r\n    .chat-send:active { transform: scale(0.95); }\r\n    .chat-send:disabled { opacity: 0.5; cursor: not-allowed; }\r\n\r\n    /* ---- RIGHT SIDEBAR ---- */\r\n    .sidebar-right {\r\n      background: var(--surface);\r\n      border-left: 1px solid var(--border);\r\n      display: flex;\r\n      flex-direction: column;\r\n      overflow: hidden;\r\n    }\r\n\r\n    .personality-panel {\r\n      padding: 16px;\r\n      border-bottom: 1px solid var(--border);\r\n    }\r\n\r\n    .trait-item {\r\n      margin-bottom: 10px;\r\n    }\r\n\r\n    .trait-header {\r\n      display: flex;\r\n      justify-content: space-between;\r\n      align-items: baseline;\r\n      margin-bottom: 4px;\r\n    }\r\n\r\n    .trait-name {\r\n      font-size: 12px;\r\n      font-weight: 600;\r\n      color: var(--text);\r\n    }\r\n\r\n    .trait-strength {\r\n      font-size: 10px;\r\n      color: var(--text-muted);\r\n    }\r\n\r\n    .trait-bar-bg {\r\n      height: 4px;\r\n      background: var(--surface2);\r\n      border-radius: 2px;\r\n      overflow: hidden;\r\n    }\r\n\r\n    .trait-bar {\r\n      height: 100%;\r\n      background: var(--accent);\r\n      border-radius: 2px;\r\n      transition: width 0.4s ease;\r\n    }\r\n\r\n    .trait-desc {\r\n      font-size: 11px;\r\n      color: var(--text-dim);\r\n      margin-top: 2px;\r\n    }\r\n\r\n    .anchor-item {\r\n      display: flex;\r\n      align-items: center;\r\n      gap: 6px;\r\n      font-size: 11px;\r\n      color: var(--text-dim);\r\n      margin-bottom: 4px;\r\n    }\r\n\r\n    .anchor-dot {\r\n      width: 5px;\r\n\n[464 more lines in file. Use offset=375 to continue.]"}],"isError":false,"timestamp":1774246550803}}
