{"type":"message","id":"a01abfd3","parentId":"34f9623f","timestamp":"2026-03-23T06:20:55.465Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Line 773 shows `b'[Error: \" + evt.content + \"]\";'` — there's no `\\n` before `[Error:`. This is the line from the SSE error handling that was broken. The original was supposed to be:\n```javascript\nnovaDiv.querySelector(\".message-bubble\").textContent += \"\\n[Error: \" + evt.content + \"]\";\n```\n\nBut after the PowerShell mangling, the `\\n` became a literal backslash-n (which would be `\\\\n` in source, or bytes `5c 6e`). After my fix, the bytes `5c 6e` (backslash-n) should have been replaced with `0a` (actual newline). But the line 773 doesn't have any newline before `[Error:` — it starts with `[Error`.\n\n\nWait, the line actually starts with `b'            [Error...'` with leading spaces, so the newline character is already there from the split. The newline before the opening quote is the line terminator itself — the `split(b'\\n')` removed them, so what I'm seeing as `b'[Error...'` is the content after that newline. So the original JavaScript string `\"\\n[Error: \"` spans across the line break — the `\\n` escape sequence is right before `[Error`, meaning there's a literal newline embedded in the string itself. My replacement should have changed those two bytes to an actual newline character, but the output still shows them as separate characters, which suggests the replacement didn't work as intended. Looking at the line numbers, the buffer splitting logic in the original SSE parsing is actually intact and functioning correctly. Let me trace through what's happening with that error string — when I split the data by newlines, the backslash-n escape sequence should be getting reconstructed properly from the individual bytes, so the error message formatting should work as intended. I need to stop second-guessing the byte-level details and just verify whether the HTML file is actually correct